revision.text:
{{also|This|thîs|þis}}
==English==
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|this}}, from {{inh|en|ang|þis}} (neuter demonstrative), from North Sea Germanic base *þa- "that", from {{der|en|gem-pro|*þat}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*tód}}, extended form of demonstrative base {{m|ine-pro|*to-}}; + North-West Germanic definitive suffix '''-s''', from {{der|en|ine-pro|*só||this, that}}.
Cognate with {{cog|sco|this||this}}, {{cog|stq|dusse||this}}, {{cog|fy|dizze||this}}, {{cog|de|dies}}, {{m|de|dieses||this}}, {{cog|non-ogt|þissi||this}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|''th''ĭs|''th''əs}}, {{IPA|en|/ðɪs/|/ðəs/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-this.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-this.wav|Audio (UK male)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɪs|s=1}}
===Determiner===
{{head|en|determiner|plural|these}}
# The (thing) here {{qualifier|used in indicating something or someone nearby}}.
#: {{ux|en|'''This''' classroom is where I learned to read and write.}}
# The known (thing) {{qualifier|used in indicating something or someone just mentioned}}.
#: {{ux|en|They give the appearance of knowing what they're doing. It's '''this''' appearance that lets them get away with so much.}}
# The known (thing) {{qualifier|used in indicating something or someone about to be mentioned}}.
#: {{ux|en|When asked what he wanted for his birthday, he gave '''this''' reply: “[…]”}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A known (thing) {{qualifier|used in first mentioning a person or thing that the speaker does not think is known to the audience}}. Compare with "''a [[certain#Determiner|certain]] ...''".
#: {{ux|en|I met '''this''' woman the other day who's allergic to wheat. I didn't even know that was possible!}}
#: {{ux|en|There's just '''this''' nervous mannerism that Bob has with his hands, and it drives me crazy.}}
# {{lb|en|of a time reference}} {{n-g|Designates the current or next instance.}}
#: {{cot|en|next}}
#: {{ux|en|It's cold '''this''' morning.}}
#: {{ux|en|I plan to go to London '''this''' Friday.}}
